/* CISA :: content/quiz2.js — CISA Domain 2 question bank (100 items). */
window.CISA = window.CISA || {}; CISA.questions = CISA.questions || [];
CISA.questions.push.apply(CISA.questions, [
{"id":"D2-001","domain":2,"obj":"2A1","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is assessing whether a publicly traded company adequately supports the reliability of its financial reporting through IT controls. Which regulation MOST directly drives the requirement for management to assess internal control over financial reporting?","options":["GDPR","PCI DSS","Sarbanes-Oxley Act (SOX)","HIPAA"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Sarbanes-Oxley Act (SOX)</strong> — SOX Sections 302 and 404 require management of U.S. public companies to assess and attest to the effectiveness of internal control over financial reporting, which includes the IT general controls supporting those systems.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>GDPR</b>: governs protection of EU personal data, not financial-reporting internal control.</span><span class='qd'><b>PCI DSS</b>: is a contractual standard for protecting cardholder data, not statutory financial-reporting control.</span><span class='qd'><b>HIPAA</b>: protects health information, unrelated to financial-statement reliability.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-002","domain":2,"obj":"2A2","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor wants to identify the framework the organization uses specifically for the governance and management of enterprise IT. Which framework is designed for that purpose?","options":["COBIT 2019","ITIL 4","PMBOK","OWASP"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>COBIT 2019</strong> — COBIT is ISACA's framework purpose-built for the governance and management of enterprise IT, distinguishing governance objectives from management objectives across the enterprise.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>ITIL 4</b>: is a best-practice framework for IT service management, not overall IT governance.</span><span class='qd'><b>PMBOK</b>: is a body of knowledge for project management.</span><span class='qd'><b>OWASP</b>: is a community focused on application security, not enterprise IT governance.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-003","domain":2,"obj":"2A3","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is classifying governance documents. Which document states a mandatory, high-level management intent and direction that everyone in the organization must follow?","options":["A guideline","A procedure","A standard","A policy"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>A policy</strong> — a policy is a high-level, mandatory statement of management intent and direction that sets the tone for all subordinate standards, procedures, and guidelines.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A guideline</b>: is discretionary advice, not a mandatory statement of intent.</span><span class='qd'><b>A procedure</b>: is a detailed step-by-step method for carrying out a task, not the high-level intent.</span><span class='qd'><b>A standard</b>: specifies mandatory rules or metrics that implement a policy but is not the top-level statement of intent.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-004","domain":2,"obj":"2A4","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor reviewing enterprise architecture documentation encounters the terms 'current state' and 'target state.' The gap between them is BEST described as the basis for what?","options":["A disaster recovery plan","A transition or migration roadmap","A vendor RFP","A data retention schedule"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>A transition or migration roadmap</strong> — enterprise architecture defines the baseline (current) and target architectures, and the difference between them drives the transition roadmap of initiatives needed to close the gap.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A disaster recovery plan</b>: addresses recovery after disruption, not the planned evolution of architecture.</span><span class='qd'><b>A vendor RFP</b>: solicits supplier proposals and is not the product of an architecture gap analysis.</span><span class='qd'><b>A data retention schedule</b>: governs how long data is kept, unrelated to architecture transition.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-005","domain":2,"obj":"2A5","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing the enterprise risk register. Risk that remains AFTER controls have been applied is known as what?","options":["Inherent risk","Residual risk","Detection risk","Systemic risk"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Residual risk</strong> — residual risk is the level of risk remaining after management applies controls or other risk-treatment measures to the inherent risk.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Inherent risk</b>: is the risk level before any controls are applied.</span><span class='qd'><b>Detection risk</b>: is an audit-risk component (the risk the auditor fails to detect a misstatement), not a residual enterprise risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>Systemic risk</b>: refers to risk that can collapse an entire system or market, not the post-control remainder.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-006","domain":2,"obj":"2A6","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor evaluates whether privacy requirements were embedded into a new system from the outset rather than added afterward. Which principle is being assessed?","options":["Least privilege","Segregation of duties","Defense in depth","Privacy by design"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Privacy by design</strong> — privacy by design requires that privacy protections be built into the design and architecture of systems and processes from the beginning, not bolted on later.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Least privilege</b>: limits access rights to the minimum needed; it is an access-control principle, not a privacy-engineering approach.</span><span class='qd'><b>Segregation of duties</b>: prevents any one person from controlling a whole transaction, unrelated to embedding privacy in design.</span><span class='qd'><b>Defense in depth</b>: layers security controls; it does not specifically address building privacy in from the start.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-007","domain":2,"obj":"2A7","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is confirming accountability for a critical customer database. Who is the party accountable for defining the data's classification and authorizing access?","options":["The data owner","The data custodian","The database administrator","The end user"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>The data owner</strong> — the data owner is the accountable business party who determines the classification of the data, defines acceptable use, and authorizes access.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The data custodian</b>: implements and maintains controls on the owner's behalf but does not set classification or authorize access.</span><span class='qd'><b>The database administrator</b>: is a custodian that operates the database technically; it does not own the data.</span><span class='qd'><b>The end user</b>: consumes the data under granted permissions and has no ownership accountability.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-008","domain":2,"obj":"2B1","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing how IT ensures sufficient processing and storage resources are available to meet future demand. Which process is being examined?","options":["Incident management","Change management","Capacity management","Problem management"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Capacity management</strong> — capacity management ensures that IT resources such as processing, storage, and bandwidth are planned and provisioned to meet current and forecasted business demand.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Incident management</b>: restores normal service after disruptions; it does not plan future resource levels.</span><span class='qd'><b>Change management</b>: controls modifications to the environment, not resource forecasting.</span><span class='qd'><b>Problem management</b>: finds root causes of recurring incidents, unrelated to capacity planning.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-009","domain":2,"obj":"2B2","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing a contract with a cloud provider and wants to confirm the auditor's ability to independently inspect the provider's controls. Which contract clause is MOST relevant?","options":["A force majeure clause","An indemnification clause","A non-compete clause","A right-to-audit clause"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>A right-to-audit clause</strong> — a right-to-audit clause preserves the customer's ability (directly or via an independent party) to examine the vendor's controls and compliance, which is essential for third-party assurance.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A force majeure clause</b>: excuses performance during extraordinary events; it grants no audit rights.</span><span class='qd'><b>An indemnification clause</b>: allocates liability for losses; it does not enable inspection.</span><span class='qd'><b>A non-compete clause</b>: restricts competitive activity, irrelevant to auditing controls.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-010","domain":2,"obj":"2B3","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor notes that IT management tracks 'percentage of incidents resolved within the agreed service level.' This measure is BEST classified as what?","options":["A key risk indicator (KRI)","A key performance indicator (KPI)","A risk appetite statement","A control objective"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>A key performance indicator (KPI)</strong> — a KPI measures how well a process is achieving its objectives; incidents resolved within the agreed service level directly gauges service-desk performance.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A key risk indicator (KRI)</b>: signals rising exposure to a risk, not attainment of a performance target.</span><span class='qd'><b>A risk appetite statement</b>: expresses how much risk the organization will accept, not a performance measure.</span><span class='qd'><b>A control objective</b>: states the desired control outcome; it is not itself a metric.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-011","domain":2,"obj":"2B4","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is assessing the maturity of the software development process using a five-level maturity model developed by the SEI. Which model is being used?","options":["ISO 9001","Six Sigma","CMMI","TOGAF"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>CMMI</strong> — Capability Maturity Model Integration provides staged maturity levels (from Initial through Optimizing) to assess and improve the maturity of development and other processes.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>ISO 9001</b>: is a quality-management-system standard; it is not a staged software-process maturity model.</span><span class='qd'><b>Six Sigma</b>: is a data-driven defect-reduction methodology, not a maturity model with SEI levels.</span><span class='qd'><b>TOGAF</b>: is an enterprise-architecture framework, unrelated to process maturity.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-012","domain":2,"obj":"2A1","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor reviews an organization that stores and processes payment card data. Which framework establishes the mandatory security controls it must meet?","options":["PCI DSS","ISO 9001","COSO","ITIL"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>PCI DSS</strong> — the Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard defines the mandatory technical and operational controls organizations must implement to protect cardholder data.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>ISO 9001</b>: addresses quality management, not payment-card security.</span><span class='qd'><b>COSO</b>: is an internal-control framework for general controls and financial reporting, not card data.</span><span class='qd'><b>ITIL</b>: covers IT service management, not cardholder-data protection.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-013","domain":2,"obj":"2A2","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor wants to confirm that the IT strategy directly supports the enterprise's business objectives. This linkage is BEST described as what?","options":["IT-business strategic alignment","Segregation of duties","Capacity planning","Change control"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>IT-business strategic alignment</strong> — strategic alignment ensures the IT strategy, investments, and services are directed toward and support the enterprise's business goals.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Segregation of duties</b>: is a control that separates conflicting responsibilities, not a strategy linkage.</span><span class='qd'><b>Capacity planning</b>: forecasts resource needs; it does not describe strategy-to-business alignment.</span><span class='qd'><b>Change control</b>: manages modifications and is unrelated to strategic direction.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-014","domain":2,"obj":"2A3","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing a document that gives detailed, sequential instructions for how staff must reset a user's password. This document is BEST categorized as what?","options":["A policy","A standard","A procedure","A guideline"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>A procedure</strong> — a procedure provides the detailed, step-by-step actions required to accomplish a specific task, such as resetting a password.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A policy</b>: states high-level intent, not step-by-step instructions.</span><span class='qd'><b>A standard</b>: sets mandatory rules or configurations but not the sequential how-to steps.</span><span class='qd'><b>A guideline</b>: offers optional recommendations, not mandatory ordered steps.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-015","domain":2,"obj":"2A5","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor reviews the four options management uses to treat an identified risk. Which set correctly lists them?","options":["Detect, prevent, correct, deter","Avoid, mitigate, transfer, accept","Identify, protect, detect, respond","Plan, do, check, act"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Avoid, mitigate, transfer, accept</strong> — the standard risk-treatment options are to avoid the risk, mitigate (reduce) it, transfer (share) it, or accept it.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Detect, prevent, correct, deter</b>: describes categories of controls, not risk-treatment decisions.</span><span class='qd'><b>Identify, protect, detect, respond</b>: are NIST Cybersecurity Framework functions, not risk-treatment options.</span><span class='qd'><b>Plan, do, check, act</b>: is the continuous-improvement (Deming) cycle, not risk treatment.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-016","domain":2,"obj":"2A6","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing how the organization evaluates privacy impacts before launching a new data-processing activity. Which assessment is designed for this?","options":["Business impact analysis (BIA)","Penetration test","Gap analysis","Privacy impact assessment (PIA)"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Privacy impact assessment (PIA)</strong> — a PIA systematically evaluates how a new or changed process affects the privacy of individuals and identifies mitigations before deployment.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Business impact analysis (BIA)</b>: assesses the operational impact of disruptions for continuity planning, not privacy.</span><span class='qd'><b>Penetration test</b>: probes technical security weaknesses, not privacy impacts.</span><span class='qd'><b>Gap analysis</b>: compares current versus desired state generally, not specifically privacy effects.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-017","domain":2,"obj":"2A7","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor reviews a scheme that labels information as Public, Internal, Confidential, and Restricted. What is this scheme called?","options":["A data retention schedule","An access control list","A data classification scheme","A data flow diagram"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>A data classification scheme</strong> — a data classification scheme assigns sensitivity levels to information so appropriate protection and handling can be applied.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A data retention schedule</b>: defines how long data is kept, not its sensitivity level.</span><span class='qd'><b>An access control list</b>: lists who may access a resource; it is an enforcement mechanism, not a classification scheme.</span><span class='qd'><b>A data flow diagram</b>: depicts how data moves through processes, not its classification.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-018","domain":2,"obj":"2B1","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing how the organization selects and balances a mix of IT projects to maximize value within budget. This discipline is BEST described as what?","options":["IT portfolio management","Incident management","Configuration management","Capacity management"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>IT portfolio management</strong> — portfolio management selects, prioritizes, and balances the collection of IT investments and projects to optimize value against resources and risk.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Incident management</b>: restores service after disruptions; it does not select investments.</span><span class='qd'><b>Configuration management</b>: tracks configuration items and their relationships, not investment selection.</span><span class='qd'><b>Capacity management</b>: forecasts resource needs, not the balance of the project mix.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-019","domain":2,"obj":"2B2","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor reviews an agreement between two internal departments that defines the support one provides to the other. What is this agreement called?","options":["A service level agreement (SLA)","An underpinning contract (UC)","A memorandum of understanding (MOU)","An operational level agreement (OLA)"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>An operational level agreement (OLA)</strong> — an OLA defines the interdependent responsibilities and support commitments between internal teams that underpin an external SLA.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A service level agreement (SLA)</b>: is between the provider and the customer, not between internal departments.</span><span class='qd'><b>An underpinning contract (UC)</b>: is with an external third-party supplier, not an internal team.</span><span class='qd'><b>A memorandum of understanding (MOU)</b>: is a non-binding statement of intent, not a defined internal support agreement.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-020","domain":2,"obj":"2B3","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor reviews a management tool that translates strategy into objectives across four perspectives: financial, customer, internal process, and learning and growth. What is this tool?","options":["The risk register","The balanced scorecard","The RACI chart","The data dictionary"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>The balanced scorecard</strong> — the balanced scorecard measures performance across financial, customer, internal-process, and learning-and-growth perspectives to link operations to strategy.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The risk register</b>: records risks and their treatment, not multi-perspective performance.</span><span class='qd'><b>The RACI chart</b>: maps responsibility roles to activities, not strategic performance measures.</span><span class='qd'><b>The data dictionary</b>: describes data elements, unrelated to performance perspectives.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-021","domain":2,"obj":"2B4","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing the organization's quality management system. Which international standard specifically defines requirements for a quality management system (QMS)?","options":["ISO/IEC 27001","ISO 9001","ISO 22301","ISO/IEC 20000"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>ISO 9001</strong> — ISO 9001 specifies the requirements for a quality management system focused on consistently meeting customer and regulatory requirements.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>ISO/IEC 27001</b>: specifies an information security management system, not a QMS.</span><span class='qd'><b>ISO 22301</b>: addresses business continuity management, not quality management.</span><span class='qd'><b>ISO/IEC 20000</b>: covers IT service management, not general quality management.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-022","domain":2,"obj":"2A1","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor reviews a European organization's handling of personal data. Which regulation grants individuals rights such as access, rectification, and erasure of their data?","options":["SOX","GLBA","FISMA","GDPR"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>GDPR</strong> — the General Data Protection Regulation grants data subjects rights including access, rectification, erasure, restriction, portability, and objection over their personal data.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>SOX</b>: governs financial-reporting controls, not individual data rights.</span><span class='qd'><b>GLBA</b>: governs U.S. financial-institution privacy, not the broad EU data-subject rights.</span><span class='qd'><b>FISMA</b>: mandates security for U.S. federal information systems, not personal-data rights.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-023","domain":2,"obj":"2A2","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor wants to know which body provides the highest-level oversight and ultimate accountability for IT governance in the enterprise. Which body is it?","options":["The board of directors","The IT steering committee","The change advisory board","The project management office"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>The board of directors</strong> — the board holds ultimate accountability for governance, including setting direction for and overseeing the enterprise's use of IT.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The IT steering committee</b>: prioritizes IT investments and advises but is subordinate to the board.</span><span class='qd'><b>The change advisory board</b>: assesses and approves changes operationally, not enterprise governance.</span><span class='qd'><b>The project management office</b>: standardizes project delivery; it does not hold governance accountability.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-024","domain":2,"obj":"2A4","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing the enterprise architecture methodology. Which framework provides the Architecture Development Method (ADM) as a step-by-step approach?","options":["COBIT","PRINCE2","TOGAF","Scrum"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>TOGAF</strong> — The Open Group Architecture Framework provides the Architecture Development Method, an iterative cycle for developing and governing enterprise architecture.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>COBIT</b>: is an IT governance framework and does not provide the ADM.</span><span class='qd'><b>PRINCE2</b>: is a project-management method, not an architecture framework.</span><span class='qd'><b>Scrum</b>: is an agile delivery framework, not an enterprise-architecture method.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-025","domain":2,"obj":"2A5","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor reviews a statement declaring the amount and type of risk the organization is willing to pursue in pursuit of its objectives. What is this called?","options":["Residual risk","Risk velocity","Risk exposure","Risk appetite"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Risk appetite</strong> — risk appetite is the broad amount and type of risk an organization is willing to accept in pursuit of its objectives, set by the board and senior management.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Residual risk</b>: is what remains after controls, not the willingness to take risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>Risk velocity</b>: is how quickly a risk materializes, not the appetite for it.</span><span class='qd'><b>Risk exposure</b>: is the potential loss from a risk, not the accepted level.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-026","domain":2,"obj":"2A6","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor finds that a marketing team collects customer birth dates and home addresses for a promotion but uses only email addresses to run it. Which privacy principle is MOST clearly violated?","options":["Non-repudiation","Data minimization","Availability","Least privilege"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Data minimization</strong> — data minimization requires collecting only the personal data necessary for the stated purpose; gathering birth dates and addresses not used for the promotion breaches it.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Non-repudiation</b>: ensures actions cannot be denied; it is unrelated to over-collection of data.</span><span class='qd'><b>Availability</b>: concerns systems being accessible, not the scope of data collected.</span><span class='qd'><b>Least privilege</b>: limits access rights, not the amount of personal data collected.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-027","domain":2,"obj":"2A7","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is distinguishing roles in data governance. Who is responsible for the day-to-day handling, quality, and consistency of data within a business area, acting as a bridge between owners and technical teams?","options":["Data owner","Data custodian","Data steward","Data subject"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Data steward</strong> — a data steward manages the day-to-day quality, definitions, and consistent use of data on behalf of the owner and coordinates with custodians and users.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Data owner</b>: is accountable for classification and access decisions but does not perform daily stewardship.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data custodian</b>: implements technical controls and storage, not business-level data quality stewardship.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data subject</b>: is the individual the personal data is about, not a governance role.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-028","domain":2,"obj":"2B1","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews how IT justifies major technology spending in business terms and measures the value delivered. Which discipline is being examined?","options":["IT investment (financial) management","Incident management","Patch management","Release management"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>IT investment (financial) management</strong> — IT investment management uses business cases, budgeting, and value measurement to justify and track the returns on technology spending.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Incident management</b>: restores service after disruptions, not investment justification.</span><span class='qd'><b>Patch management</b>: applies software updates, unrelated to financial value tracking.</span><span class='qd'><b>Release management</b>: coordinates deployment of changes, not investment value.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-029","domain":2,"obj":"2B2","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor learns that a key supplier outsources part of its service to a subcontractor that also handles the organization's data. The risk introduced by this subcontractor is BEST described as what?","options":["Fourth-party (subcontractor) risk","Inherent audit risk","Sampling risk","Detection risk"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Fourth-party (subcontractor) risk</strong> — fourth-party risk arises from the subcontractors of your direct vendors, extending the supply chain and requiring flow-down controls and oversight.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Inherent audit risk</b>: is the susceptibility to misstatement before controls, an audit concept, not a supply-chain exposure.</span><span class='qd'><b>Sampling risk</b>: is the risk a sample is not representative, unrelated to subcontractors.</span><span class='qd'><b>Detection risk</b>: is the risk the audit fails to detect an issue, not vendor supply-chain risk.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-030","domain":2,"obj":"2B3","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor notes IT compares its incident-resolution times against those of peer organizations. This practice is BEST described as what?","options":["Sampling","Regression testing","Benchmarking","Root cause analysis"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Benchmarking</strong> — benchmarking compares an organization's performance metrics against peers or industry standards to identify improvement opportunities.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Sampling</b>: selects a subset of items for testing, not a comparison against peers.</span><span class='qd'><b>Regression testing</b>: verifies that changes did not break existing functionality, unrelated to peer comparison.</span><span class='qd'><b>Root cause analysis</b>: determines why an incident occurred, not comparative performance.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-031","domain":2,"obj":"2B4","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing the difference between quality assurance and quality control. Which statement BEST distinguishes quality assurance (QA)?","options":["QA inspects finished products to find defects after the fact","QA is process-oriented and prevents defects by improving the process","QA is performed only by external auditors","QA replaces the need for testing"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>QA is process-oriented and prevents defects by improving the process</strong> — quality assurance focuses on the processes used to build a product, aiming to prevent defects, whereas quality control detects defects in the output.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>QA inspects finished products to find defects after the fact</b>: describes quality control, not QA.</span><span class='qd'><b>QA is performed only by external auditors</b>: QA is an internal process discipline, not exclusive to external auditors.</span><span class='qd'><b>QA replaces the need for testing</b>: QA and testing (a form of quality control) are complementary, not substitutes.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-032","domain":2,"obj":"2A1","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is verifying that an organization's information security management system (ISMS) is certified against a recognized international standard. Which standard would the certification reference?","options":["ISO 9001","ISO 14001","ISO 31000","ISO/IEC 27001"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>ISO/IEC 27001</strong> — ISO/IEC 27001 specifies the requirements for establishing, implementing, and certifying an information security management system.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>ISO 9001</b>: certifies quality management systems, not information security.</span><span class='qd'><b>ISO 14001</b>: certifies environmental management systems.</span><span class='qd'><b>ISO 31000</b>: provides risk-management guidance and is not a certifiable ISMS standard.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-033","domain":2,"obj":"2A2","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor evaluates an IT steering committee. Which characteristic would MOST concern the auditor about its effectiveness?","options":["It includes representatives from major business units","It maintains documented minutes of decisions","It has no senior business management participation","It prioritizes projects against the strategic plan"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>It has no senior business management participation</strong> — without senior business representation, the steering committee cannot ensure IT investments align with business priorities or command the authority to enforce decisions.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It includes representatives from major business units</b>: this is a strength, ensuring business input, not a concern.</span><span class='qd'><b>It maintains documented minutes of decisions</b>: documentation supports accountability and is a positive attribute.</span><span class='qd'><b>It prioritizes projects against the strategic plan</b>: aligning projects to strategy is exactly what an effective committee should do.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-034","domain":2,"obj":"2A3","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor finds that the organization has a comprehensive information security policy but no supporting standards or procedures. What is the MOST significant concern?","options":["The policy will be difficult to implement consistently","The policy is too detailed for staff to read","Standards should always precede policies","Procedures are optional in every organization"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>The policy will be difficult to implement consistently</strong> — without standards and procedures to translate high-level intent into concrete rules and steps, staff cannot apply the policy uniformly, weakening its effectiveness.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The policy is too detailed for staff to read</b>: a policy is high-level by design; excessive detail is not the described issue.</span><span class='qd'><b>Standards should always precede policies</b>: this is backwards; policies set intent that standards then implement.</span><span class='qd'><b>Procedures are optional in every organization</b>: procedures are needed to operationalize controls, so this understates the concern.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-035","domain":2,"obj":"2A4","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is assessing whether new solutions comply with the approved enterprise architecture. Which governance body typically reviews solutions for architectural compliance and grants exceptions?","options":["The change advisory board","The disaster recovery team","The internal audit committee","The architecture review board"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>The architecture review board</strong> — the architecture review board evaluates proposed solutions against the enterprise architecture, enforcing standards and authorizing justified exceptions.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The change advisory board</b>: assesses operational changes for risk and scheduling, not architectural compliance.</span><span class='qd'><b>The disaster recovery team</b>: focuses on recovery capability, not architecture conformance.</span><span class='qd'><b>The internal audit committee</b>: oversees the audit function independently and does not grant architecture exceptions.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-036","domain":2,"obj":"2A5","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews a metric that management monitors to provide an early warning that a risk is approaching an unacceptable level. This metric is BEST described as what?","options":["A key performance indicator (KPI)","A key risk indicator (KRI)","A service level target","A control self-assessment"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>A key risk indicator (KRI)</strong> — a KRI is a forward-looking metric that signals a rising level of exposure so management can act before a threshold is breached.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A key performance indicator (KPI)</b>: measures achievement of objectives, not early warning of risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>A service level target</b>: defines an agreed performance level, not risk warning.</span><span class='qd'><b>A control self-assessment</b>: is a process for evaluating controls, not a monitored indicator.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-037","domain":2,"obj":"2A6","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews the lawful basis an organization relies on to process personal data for a newsletter. The organization obtained clear, affirmative opt-in from each subscriber. Which basis is being relied upon?","options":["Legitimate interest","Consent","Legal obligation","Vital interest"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Consent</strong> — a clear, affirmative opt-in constitutes consent, one of the recognized lawful bases for processing personal data.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Legitimate interest</b>: relies on a balancing test rather than the subject's opt-in and is not what the affirmative opt-in describes.</span><span class='qd'><b>Legal obligation</b>: applies when a law compels processing, which is not the case for a newsletter.</span><span class='qd'><b>Vital interest</b>: applies to protecting someone's life, not marketing communications.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-038","domain":2,"obj":"2A7","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor wants to confirm that a data owner has properly delegated protection responsibilities. To whom does the owner typically delegate the operational safeguarding of the data?","options":["The data subject","The regulator","The internal auditor","The data custodian"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>The data custodian</strong> — the data owner delegates the implementation and operation of protective controls (backup, access enforcement, storage) to the data custodian.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The data subject</b>: is the person the data concerns and holds no protective duty.</span><span class='qd'><b>The regulator</b>: enforces law externally and is not delegated operational safeguarding.</span><span class='qd'><b>The internal auditor</b>: independently evaluates controls and must not operate them, to preserve independence.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-039","domain":2,"obj":"2B1","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews how IT ensures it has staff with the right skills for current and future needs. Which practice is being assessed?","options":["Competency and workforce management","Configuration management","Capacity management","Vendor management"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Competency and workforce management</strong> — this practice plans and develops the skills, roles, and capacity of IT personnel to meet current and future demands.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Configuration management</b>: tracks configuration items, not staff skills.</span><span class='qd'><b>Capacity management</b>: forecasts technical resource needs, not human competencies.</span><span class='qd'><b>Vendor management</b>: governs third-party suppliers, not internal workforce skills.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-040","domain":2,"obj":"2B2","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is evaluating the vendor-selection process. During which stage does the organization formally solicit detailed proposals from candidate suppliers to compare their offerings?","options":["Business case approval","Contract termination","Request for proposal (RFP)","Right-to-audit exercise"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Request for proposal (RFP)</strong> — an RFP formally solicits detailed proposals from candidate vendors so the organization can compare capabilities, terms, and pricing before selection.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Business case approval</b>: justifies the investment internally and precedes soliciting supplier proposals.</span><span class='qd'><b>Contract termination</b>: ends an existing agreement, not a selection activity.</span><span class='qd'><b>Right-to-audit exercise</b>: is an oversight activity during the relationship, not proposal solicitation.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-041","domain":2,"obj":"2B3","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews an IT performance report to the board that shows only server uptime percentages. What is the auditor's MOST valid concern about this report as a governance tool?","options":["Uptime is not a valid technical measure","The report is too frequent for the board","Server uptime cannot be measured objectively","It does not link IT performance to business outcomes and value"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>It does not link IT performance to business outcomes and value</strong> — effective governance reporting connects IT metrics to business value and objectives; a purely technical uptime figure gives the board no view of value delivery or risk.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Uptime is not a valid technical measure</b>: uptime is a legitimate operational metric; the issue is its narrow, non-business focus.</span><span class='qd'><b>The report is too frequent for the board</b>: frequency is not the described problem; relevance to governance is.</span><span class='qd'><b>Server uptime cannot be measured objectively</b>: uptime is highly objective and measurable.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-042","domain":2,"obj":"2B4","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor examines the enterprise's quality program and finds it built around plan-do-check-act cycles for ongoing refinement. This approach BEST reflects which quality concept?","options":["Waterfall delivery","Continuous improvement","Big-bang implementation","Segregation of duties"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Continuous improvement</strong> — the plan-do-check-act (Deming) cycle is the foundation of continuous quality improvement, iteratively refining processes over time.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Waterfall delivery</b>: is a sequential development approach, not a quality-improvement cycle.</span><span class='qd'><b>Big-bang implementation</b>: is a deployment strategy, not a quality concept.</span><span class='qd'><b>Segregation of duties</b>: is an internal control, unrelated to iterative quality refinement.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-043","domain":2,"obj":"2A1","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is assessing a healthcare provider's protection of patient records. Which U.S. regulation establishes the security and privacy requirements for protected health information?","options":["SOX","PCI DSS","HIPAA","COPPA"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>HIPAA</strong> — the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act sets the Privacy and Security Rules governing the protection of protected health information.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>SOX</b>: governs financial-reporting controls, not health information.</span><span class='qd'><b>PCI DSS</b>: protects payment-card data, not patient records.</span><span class='qd'><b>COPPA</b>: protects children's online privacy, not health records generally.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-044","domain":2,"obj":"2A2","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor references the international standard that provides principles for the corporate governance of IT to boards and executives. Which standard is this?","options":["ISO/IEC 38500","ISO/IEC 27002","ISO 9001","ISO 22301"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>ISO/IEC 38500</strong> — ISO/IEC 38500 provides guiding principles for the effective, efficient, and acceptable corporate governance of IT by directors and top management.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>ISO/IEC 27002</b>: gives information-security control guidance, not IT governance principles.</span><span class='qd'><b>ISO 9001</b>: specifies quality-management-system requirements.</span><span class='qd'><b>ISO 22301</b>: addresses business continuity, not IT governance.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-045","domain":2,"obj":"2A3","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing document hierarchy. A statement that recommends a preferred but non-mandatory way of doing something is BEST classified as what?","options":["A guideline","A policy","A standard","A procedure"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>A guideline</strong> — a guideline provides recommended, discretionary guidance to help apply policies and standards, but compliance is not mandatory.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A policy</b>: is a mandatory high-level statement of intent, not optional advice.</span><span class='qd'><b>A standard</b>: is mandatory and specifies required rules or configurations.</span><span class='qd'><b>A procedure</b>: is mandatory step-by-step instruction, not discretionary advice.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-046","domain":2,"obj":"2A4","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing enterprise architecture domains. Which domain describes the business processes, functions, and organization structure the architecture must support?","options":["Technology architecture","Data architecture","Business architecture","Application architecture"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Business architecture</strong> — the business architecture domain captures the organization's strategy, processes, functions, and structure that the other architecture domains are designed to support.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Technology architecture</b>: describes the hardware, networks, and platforms, not business processes.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data architecture</b>: describes data structures and their management, not business functions.</span><span class='qd'><b>Application architecture</b>: describes the applications and their interactions, not the business structure.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-047","domain":2,"obj":"2A5","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews a decision in which management chose to purchase cyber-insurance to address a high-impact but low-likelihood risk. Which risk-treatment option was selected?","options":["Avoid","Transfer","Mitigate","Accept"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Transfer</strong> — buying insurance shifts the financial consequence of the risk to a third party, which is the transfer (sharing) treatment option.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Avoid</b>: would mean ceasing the activity that creates the risk, not insuring it.</span><span class='qd'><b>Mitigate</b>: would reduce likelihood or impact through controls, not shift the financial loss.</span><span class='qd'><b>Accept</b>: would mean retaining the risk without action, which insurance does not do.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-048","domain":2,"obj":"2A6","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor evaluates whether individuals can obtain a copy of the personal data an organization holds about them. Which data subject right is being tested?","options":["Right to erasure","Right to portability","Right to object","Right of access"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Right of access</strong> — the right of access lets individuals obtain confirmation that their data is processed and a copy of that personal data.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Right to erasure</b>: allows deletion of data, not obtaining a copy.</span><span class='qd'><b>Right to portability</b>: allows transfer of data to another controller in a machine-readable format, a distinct right.</span><span class='qd'><b>Right to object</b>: allows objection to certain processing, not obtaining a copy.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-049","domain":2,"obj":"2A7","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor finds that highly sensitive records and public brochures are both stored with identical access controls. What data governance weakness does this MOST indicate?","options":["Encryption keys are too short","Retention periods are too long","Classification is not driving control selection","Data is not backed up frequently enough"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Classification is not driving control selection</strong> — controls should be commensurate with data sensitivity; applying identical controls to highly sensitive and public data shows classification is not influencing protection decisions.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Encryption keys are too short</b>: the scenario says nothing about key length, so this is not indicated.</span><span class='qd'><b>Retention periods are too long</b>: retention is unrelated to the mismatch between sensitivity and controls.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data is not backed up frequently enough</b>: backup frequency is not the issue described.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-050","domain":2,"obj":"2B1","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing whether the organization gets the best value from software licenses it already owns and avoids paying for unused capacity. Which resource-management activity is being examined?","options":["Software asset and license management","Incident management","Access recertification","Penetration testing"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Software asset and license management</strong> — this activity optimizes the acquisition, use, and reconciliation of software licenses to avoid over-purchasing and non-compliance.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Incident management</b>: handles service disruptions, not license optimization.</span><span class='qd'><b>Access recertification</b>: reviews user access rights, unrelated to license value.</span><span class='qd'><b>Penetration testing</b>: probes security weaknesses, not license usage.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-051","domain":2,"obj":"2B2","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews the metrics used to hold a vendor accountable for delivery. Which document defines the measurable service commitments the vendor must meet?","options":["The request for information (RFI)","The non-disclosure agreement (NDA)","The statement of work archive","The service level agreement (SLA)"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>The service level agreement (SLA)</strong> — the SLA defines the measurable service targets, responsibilities, and remedies that the vendor is contractually bound to meet.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The request for information (RFI)</b>: gathers preliminary supplier information before selection, not delivery commitments.</span><span class='qd'><b>The non-disclosure agreement (NDA)</b>: protects confidential information, not service performance.</span><span class='qd'><b>The statement of work archive</b>: stores past work descriptions and does not set ongoing measurable targets.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-052","domain":2,"obj":"2B3","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor observes that IT reports both KPIs and KRIs to governance. What is the PRIMARY value of reporting KRIs alongside KPIs?","options":["They replace the need for KPIs entirely","They provide forward-looking warning of emerging risk, complementing performance data","They measure only financial results","They eliminate the need for a risk register"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>They provide forward-looking warning of emerging risk, complementing performance data</strong> — KRIs give an early, predictive view of rising risk that balances the achievement-focused view provided by KPIs, giving governance a fuller picture.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>They replace the need for KPIs entirely</b>: KRIs complement, not replace, performance indicators.</span><span class='qd'><b>They measure only financial results</b>: KRIs measure risk exposure across many areas, not only finance.</span><span class='qd'><b>They eliminate the need for a risk register</b>: a risk register remains the record of risks; KRIs monitor selected ones.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-053","domain":2,"obj":"2B4","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing a QMS and wants evidence that quality objectives are being met. Which artifact would provide the BEST evidence?","options":["A signed employee handbook","Quality metrics with results tracked against targets","The organization chart","The data center floor plan"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Quality metrics with results tracked against targets</strong> — measured quality metrics compared to defined targets provide direct, objective evidence that quality objectives are being achieved.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A signed employee handbook</b>: shows acknowledgement of rules, not quality-objective attainment.</span><span class='qd'><b>The organization chart</b>: shows reporting lines, not quality results.</span><span class='qd'><b>The data center floor plan</b>: describes facility layout, unrelated to quality objectives.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-054","domain":2,"obj":"2A1","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is determining which requirements are legally binding versus voluntary. Which of the following is a mandatory legal obligation rather than a voluntary standard?","options":["ISO/IEC 27001 certification","Adoption of the COBIT framework","Use of the ITIL service model","A statutory data-breach notification law"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>A statutory data-breach notification law</strong> — a statute is enacted law and is legally binding, unlike voluntary frameworks and certifications an organization may choose to adopt.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>ISO/IEC 27001 certification</b>: is a voluntary standard an organization elects to pursue.</span><span class='qd'><b>Adoption of the COBIT framework</b>: is a voluntary governance choice, not a legal mandate.</span><span class='qd'><b>Use of the ITIL service model</b>: is a voluntary best-practice adoption, not law.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-055","domain":2,"obj":"2A2","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is evaluating IT governance using COBIT 2019. In COBIT, how are governance objectives distinguished from management objectives?","options":["Governance objectives (EDM) direct and monitor; management objectives (PBRM) plan, build, run, and monitor","Governance and management objectives are identical in COBIT","Management objectives are set by the board only","Governance objectives are optional in COBIT"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Governance objectives (EDM) direct and monitor; management objectives (PBRM) plan, build, run, and monitor</strong> — COBIT 2019 separates governance (Evaluate, Direct, Monitor) performed by the board from management objectives grouped into Plan, Build, Run, and Monitor.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Governance and management objectives are identical in COBIT</b>: COBIT deliberately separates the two.</span><span class='qd'><b>Management objectives are set by the board only</b>: management objectives are executed by management, with the board handling governance.</span><span class='qd'><b>Governance objectives are optional in COBIT</b>: governance objectives are core to the framework, not optional.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-056","domain":2,"obj":"2A3","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor finds several IT policies were last reviewed six years ago with no evidence of periodic review. What is the auditor's PRIMARY concern?","options":["The policies are stored in the wrong folder","Six-year-old policies are automatically invalid by law","The policies may no longer reflect current risks, technology, and regulations","Policies never require review once approved"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>The policies may no longer reflect current risks, technology, and regulations</strong> — without periodic review, policies drift out of alignment with the evolving environment, undermining their relevance and effectiveness.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The policies are stored in the wrong folder</b>: storage location is not the governance concern raised by stale review.</span><span class='qd'><b>Six-year-old policies are automatically invalid by law</b>: age alone does not legally void a policy; relevance is the issue.</span><span class='qd'><b>Policies never require review once approved</b>: this is incorrect; policies require periodic review.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-057","domain":2,"obj":"2A4","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is assessing the benefit of a well-governed enterprise architecture. Which outcome is MOST directly enabled by mature enterprise architecture?","options":["Elimination of all project risk","Guaranteed zero system downtime","Removal of the need for change management","Reduced redundancy and better alignment of IT investments with strategy"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Reduced redundancy and better alignment of IT investments with strategy</strong> — enterprise architecture standardizes and rationalizes technology, cutting duplication and aligning investments with the business strategy and target state.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Elimination of all project risk</b>: architecture reduces some risk but cannot eliminate all project risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>Guaranteed zero system downtime</b>: no architecture guarantees zero downtime.</span><span class='qd'><b>Removal of the need for change management</b>: change management remains essential regardless of architecture maturity.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-058","domain":2,"obj":"2A5","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews the ERM program and notes management distinguishes 'risk appetite' from 'risk tolerance.' How do these terms differ?","options":["They are synonyms used interchangeably","Appetite is the broad level of risk pursued; tolerance is the acceptable variation around specific objectives","Tolerance is set by the board and appetite by staff","Appetite applies only to financial risk"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Appetite is the broad level of risk pursued; tolerance is the acceptable variation around specific objectives</strong> — risk appetite is the enterprise-wide willingness to take risk, while risk tolerance defines the acceptable deviation for a particular objective or metric.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>They are synonyms used interchangeably</b>: the terms have distinct, defined meanings.</span><span class='qd'><b>Tolerance is set by the board and appetite by staff</b>: appetite is set at the top; tolerances operationalize it, so this reverses the relationship.</span><span class='qd'><b>Appetite applies only to financial risk</b>: appetite spans all risk types, not just financial.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-059","domain":2,"obj":"2A6","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing roles under privacy regulation. Which party determines the purposes and means of processing personal data and bears primary accountability?","options":["The data processor","The data subject","The data controller","The supervisory authority"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>The data controller</strong> — the controller determines why and how personal data is processed and is primarily accountable for compliance with privacy obligations.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The data processor</b>: processes data on the controller's behalf under instruction, with narrower accountability.</span><span class='qd'><b>The data subject</b>: is the individual the data is about, not the accountable party for processing.</span><span class='qd'><b>The supervisory authority</b>: is the regulator that enforces the law, not the processing decision-maker.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-060","domain":2,"obj":"2A7","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor evaluates a data governance program's effectiveness. Which element is MOST important to confirm is in place first?","options":["Clearly assigned data ownership and accountability","A choice of columnar database technology","A social media monitoring tool","A public-facing data dashboard"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Clearly assigned data ownership and accountability</strong> — without defined owners accountable for data, classification, quality, and access decisions lack authority, so ownership is the foundational element of data governance.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A choice of columnar database technology</b>: is a technical decision, not a governance foundation.</span><span class='qd'><b>A social media monitoring tool</b>: is unrelated to establishing data governance accountability.</span><span class='qd'><b>A public-facing data dashboard</b>: is an output, not the governance foundation.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-061","domain":2,"obj":"2B1","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews how IT decides which of many competing initiatives to fund in the coming year. Which governance input MOST appropriately drives this prioritization?","options":["Alignment with business strategy and expected value","The seniority of the requesting manager","The order in which requests were received","The physical size of each project team"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Alignment with business strategy and expected value</strong> — investment prioritization should be driven by strategic alignment and the value each initiative delivers relative to cost and risk.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The seniority of the requesting manager</b>: prioritizing by rank rather than value is a governance weakness.</span><span class='qd'><b>The order in which requests were received</b>: first-come sequencing ignores strategic value.</span><span class='qd'><b>The physical size of each project team</b>: team size does not indicate business value or alignment.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-062","domain":2,"obj":"2B2","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing vendor oversight and asks for the provider's independent assurance report on its controls. Which report is MOST commonly requested for this purpose?","options":["A marketing brochure","An internal newsletter","A SOC 2 report","A sales forecast"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>A SOC 2 report</strong> — a SOC 2 report provides independent assurance over a service organization's controls relevant to security, availability, confidentiality, processing integrity, and privacy.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A marketing brochure</b>: is promotional material with no independent assurance value.</span><span class='qd'><b>An internal newsletter</b>: is informal communication, not a controls-assurance report.</span><span class='qd'><b>A sales forecast</b>: projects revenue and provides no control assurance.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-063","domain":2,"obj":"2B3","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor finds IT reports many KPIs but none tie back to defined targets or thresholds. What is the MOST significant weakness?","options":["There are too few KPIs to be useful","Without targets, performance cannot be evaluated as acceptable or not","KPIs should never be reported to management","Targets are only relevant to KRIs, not KPIs"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Without targets, performance cannot be evaluated as acceptable or not</strong> — a KPI is meaningful only against a defined target or threshold; without one, management cannot judge whether performance is satisfactory.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>There are too few KPIs to be useful</b>: the scenario describes many KPIs, so quantity is not the issue.</span><span class='qd'><b>KPIs should never be reported to management</b>: reporting KPIs to management is appropriate.</span><span class='qd'><b>Targets are only relevant to KRIs, not KPIs</b>: KPIs also require targets to be interpretable.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-064","domain":2,"obj":"2B4","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing whether the organization's quality management is aligned to a customer-focused, process-based, evidence-driven approach. Which set of principles underlies this?","options":["The OWASP Top Ten","The CIA triad","The five phases of penetration testing","ISO 9000 quality management principles"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>ISO 9000 quality management principles</strong> — the ISO 9000 family sets out quality-management principles such as customer focus, process approach, evidence-based decision-making, and continual improvement.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The OWASP Top Ten</b>: lists web application security risks, not quality principles.</span><span class='qd'><b>The CIA triad</b>: describes confidentiality, integrity, availability for security, not quality management.</span><span class='qd'><b>The five phases of penetration testing</b>: describes an offensive security process, unrelated to quality principles.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-065","domain":2,"obj":"2A1","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor notes the organization operates in multiple jurisdictions with conflicting data laws. What should the auditor recommend as the MOST appropriate approach?","options":["Comply only with the law of the head office country","Ignore foreign laws entirely","Identify all applicable requirements and comply with the most stringent","Choose whichever law is least costly to follow"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Identify all applicable requirements and comply with the most stringent</strong> — where laws conflict, meeting the most stringent applicable requirement generally satisfies the others and limits legal exposure across jurisdictions.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Comply only with the law of the head office country</b>: ignores obligations in other jurisdictions where the organization operates.</span><span class='qd'><b>Ignore foreign laws entirely</b>: creates legal and regulatory exposure abroad.</span><span class='qd'><b>Choose whichever law is least costly to follow</b>: cost does not determine legal applicability and risks non-compliance.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-066","domain":2,"obj":"2A2","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor wants to confirm the board is fulfilling its IT oversight role. Which evidence would BEST demonstrate active board-level IT governance?","options":["Board minutes showing review of IT strategy, risk, and investment decisions","A copy of the network diagram","The help desk ticket log","The server patch history"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Board minutes showing review of IT strategy, risk, and investment decisions</strong> — documented board deliberation and decisions on IT strategy, risk, and investments demonstrate that oversight is actually being exercised.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A copy of the network diagram</b>: is a technical artifact, not evidence of board oversight.</span><span class='qd'><b>The help desk ticket log</b>: shows operational support activity, not governance.</span><span class='qd'><b>The server patch history</b>: reflects operational maintenance, not board-level oversight.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-067","domain":2,"obj":"2A3","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is testing whether an acceptable use policy is effective. Which test provides the STRONGEST evidence that the policy is operating, not just existing?","options":["The policy is posted on the intranet","The policy has an approval signature","The policy uses a standard template","Evidence that violations are detected and consistently enforced"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Evidence that violations are detected and consistently enforced</strong> — a policy is only effective if breaches are identified and acted upon consistently; enforcement evidence shows it operates in practice.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The policy is posted on the intranet</b>: availability shows existence, not operating effectiveness.</span><span class='qd'><b>The policy has an approval signature</b>: approval shows authorization, not that it is enforced.</span><span class='qd'><b>The policy uses a standard template</b>: formatting says nothing about whether it operates.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-068","domain":2,"obj":"2A4","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews a proposal to adopt many overlapping tools that duplicate existing capabilities. Which enterprise architecture principle is being undermined?","options":["Segregation of duties","Technology standardization and rationalization","Least privilege","Non-repudiation"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Technology standardization and rationalization</strong> — a core EA principle is to standardize and rationalize technology to avoid duplication; adopting overlapping tools directly undermines it.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Segregation of duties</b>: is an access-control principle, unrelated to tool duplication.</span><span class='qd'><b>Least privilege</b>: concerns minimal access rights, not technology overlap.</span><span class='qd'><b>Non-repudiation</b>: ensures actions cannot be denied, not architectural rationalization.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-069","domain":2,"obj":"2A5","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews the risk register and finds risks are recorded but never assigned an owner or reassessed. What is the PRIMARY consequence?","options":["The register will be too short","Risks may not be actively monitored or treated, leaving exposure unmanaged","Inherent risk will automatically decrease","Residual risk cannot exist without ownership"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Risks may not be actively monitored or treated, leaving exposure unmanaged</strong> — without an accountable owner and periodic reassessment, risks are neither tracked nor treated, so exposure goes unmanaged over time.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The register will be too short</b>: length is not the consequence of missing ownership.</span><span class='qd'><b>Inherent risk will automatically decrease</b>: inherent risk does not fall simply because ownership is absent.</span><span class='qd'><b>Residual risk cannot exist without ownership</b>: residual risk exists regardless of whether an owner is assigned.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-070","domain":2,"obj":"2A6","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing a data-processing arrangement and wants to confirm a legally required document governs the controller-processor relationship. Which document is this?","options":["A software escrow agreement","A capacity plan","A change request form","A data processing agreement (DPA)"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>A data processing agreement (DPA)</strong> — a DPA sets out the processor's obligations, security measures, and processing limits on behalf of the controller and is required by privacy regulation.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A software escrow agreement</b>: safeguards source code access, not personal-data processing terms.</span><span class='qd'><b>A capacity plan</b>: forecasts resource needs, unrelated to controller-processor duties.</span><span class='qd'><b>A change request form</b>: authorizes a change, not data-processing obligations.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-071","domain":2,"obj":"2A7","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor finds a data classification policy exists, but sampled documents are unlabeled and staff apply protection inconsistently. Which recommendation should the auditor make FIRST?","options":["Assign data owners and require them to classify and label their data","Encrypt every document in the organization by default","Delete all unlabeled documents immediately","Purchase a new data loss prevention appliance"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Assign data owners and require them to classify and label their data</strong> — classification must be driven by accountable owners; establishing ownership and labeling is the necessary first step before protective technologies can be applied correctly.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Encrypt every document in the organization by default</b>: blanket encryption without classification wastes resources and still leaves handling undefined.</span><span class='qd'><b>Delete all unlabeled documents immediately</b>: destroying data before classification could remove records that must be retained and is disproportionate.</span><span class='qd'><b>Purchase a new data loss prevention appliance</b>: a tool cannot enforce protection without a working classification scheme to act on.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-072","domain":2,"obj":"2A5","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor reviews a risk assessment where management rated a risk's inherent likelihood as low but its residual likelihood as high. What should the auditor conclude about this rating?","options":["It is normal and requires no follow-up","It proves controls are highly effective","It is illogical because residual risk should not exceed inherent risk","It means the risk should be removed from the register"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>It is illogical because residual risk should not exceed inherent risk</strong> — residual risk is what remains after controls reduce inherent risk, so it cannot logically be higher than inherent risk; the auditor should question the assessment's integrity.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It is normal and requires no follow-up</b>: the inconsistency is abnormal and warrants investigation.</span><span class='qd'><b>It proves controls are highly effective</b>: effective controls would lower, not raise, residual risk below inherent.</span><span class='qd'><b>It means the risk should be removed from the register</b>: removing the risk hides the flaw rather than correcting the flawed rating.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-073","domain":2,"obj":"2B2","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor reviews a critical outsourcing contract and finds no exit or transition clause. What is the MOST significant risk this creates?","options":["The vendor will overcharge for the RFP","The SLA cannot include uptime targets","The organization cannot pay invoices","Vendor lock-in that impedes migrating services if the relationship ends"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Vendor lock-in that impedes migrating services if the relationship ends</strong> — without exit and transition provisions, the organization may be unable to retrieve data or move services smoothly, creating dependency and continuity risk.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The vendor will overcharge for the RFP</b>: the RFP precedes the contract and is unrelated to exit terms.</span><span class='qd'><b>The SLA cannot include uptime targets</b>: exit clauses have no bearing on whether SLAs specify uptime.</span><span class='qd'><b>The organization cannot pay invoices</b>: payment ability is independent of exit provisions.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-074","domain":2,"obj":"2A2","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor observes that IT makes major technology decisions with no reference to the business strategy, and business units acquire their own systems independently. What does this MOST likely indicate?","options":["Strong decentralized innovation that should be praised","A lack of IT governance leading to misalignment and shadow IT","Effective segregation of duties","A mature enterprise architecture"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>A lack of IT governance leading to misalignment and shadow IT</strong> — decisions divorced from strategy plus uncontrolled independent acquisitions are classic symptoms of weak IT governance, producing misalignment and unmanaged shadow IT.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Strong decentralized innovation that should be praised</b>: uncontrolled acquisition without governance creates risk, not commendable innovation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Effective segregation of duties</b>: the scenario describes governance gaps, not duty separation.</span><span class='qd'><b>A mature enterprise architecture</b>: independent, unaligned purchases are the opposite of architectural maturity.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-075","domain":2,"obj":"2A1","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor is evaluating compliance responsibilities. When a regulation applies to an outsourced process, who retains ultimate accountability for compliance?","options":["The outsourced service provider alone","The regulator that issued the rule","The organization that owns the process (the client)","The external financial auditor"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>The organization that owns the process (the client)</strong> — accountability for regulatory compliance cannot be outsourced; the client organization remains ultimately responsible even when a provider performs the work.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The outsourced service provider alone</b>: the provider is responsible for performance but does not absorb the client's ultimate accountability.</span><span class='qd'><b>The regulator that issued the rule</b>: the regulator enforces the rule; it does not bear the regulated entity's compliance accountability.</span><span class='qd'><b>The external financial auditor</b>: provides assurance and does not assume accountability for compliance.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-076","domain":2,"obj":"2A3","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor finds that IT standards mandate specific encryption algorithms, but a business unit adopted a weaker algorithm citing performance. Management approved it without documenting a formal exception. What is the auditor's PRIMARY concern?","options":["Deviations from standards are occurring without a governed exception process","Encryption standards are unnecessary for business units","Performance should always override security standards","Standards may be ignored whenever convenient"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Deviations from standards are occurring without a governed exception process</strong> — allowing undocumented deviations undermines the standards regime; deviations should flow through a formal, risk-assessed, and approved exception process.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Encryption standards are unnecessary for business units</b>: standards apply enterprise-wide, so this is incorrect.</span><span class='qd'><b>Performance should always override security standards</b>: performance may justify a documented exception but does not automatically override standards.</span><span class='qd'><b>Standards may be ignored whenever convenient</b>: ignoring standards at will is exactly the governance failure the auditor is flagging.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-077","domain":2,"obj":"2A4","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor is assessing enterprise architecture governance. Which finding would MOST undermine the value of the architecture?","options":["Projects routinely bypass architecture review with no enforcement","The architecture defines both current and target states","The architecture is approved by an architecture review board","The architecture is periodically updated"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Projects routinely bypass architecture review with no enforcement</strong> — if architecture standards are not enforced and projects circumvent review, the architecture cannot guide the estate and its intended benefits are lost.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The architecture defines both current and target states</b>: this is a strength that enables gap analysis and roadmaps.</span><span class='qd'><b>The architecture is approved by an architecture review board</b>: formal approval strengthens governance, not undermines it.</span><span class='qd'><b>The architecture is periodically updated</b>: keeping it current is a positive attribute.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-078","domain":2,"obj":"2A5","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor reviews an enterprise risk management program in which risk decisions are made independently by each department with no aggregation. What is the MOST significant limitation of this approach?","options":["Departments will never identify any risks","Residual risk becomes equal to inherent risk","The enterprise cannot see aggregate or interdependent risk exposure","Risk appetite becomes irrelevant to operations"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>The enterprise cannot see aggregate or interdependent risk exposure</strong> — siloed risk decisions prevent the enterprise from understanding combined and correlated exposures, which is the very purpose of enterprise-wide risk management.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Departments will never identify any risks</b>: departments can still identify local risks; the gap is aggregation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Residual risk becomes equal to inherent risk</b>: siloed decisions do not force this equivalence.</span><span class='qd'><b>Risk appetite becomes irrelevant to operations</b>: appetite still matters; the problem is it cannot be applied enterprise-wide without aggregation.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-079","domain":2,"obj":"2A6","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor is evaluating a privacy program. A new analytics platform will repurpose customer data originally collected for order fulfillment. Which principle is MOST at risk, and what control BEST addresses it?","options":["Availability; increase server redundancy","Purpose limitation; conduct a PIA and obtain a valid lawful basis for the new use","Non-repudiation; deploy digital signatures","Integrity; add checksums to the data"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Purpose limitation; conduct a PIA and obtain a valid lawful basis for the new use</strong> — reusing data for a new, incompatible purpose challenges purpose limitation; a PIA and a fresh lawful basis (such as consent) are the appropriate controls.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Availability; increase server redundancy</b>: availability is not the privacy principle threatened by repurposing.</span><span class='qd'><b>Non-repudiation; deploy digital signatures</b>: non-repudiation concerns proof of action, not lawful reuse of data.</span><span class='qd'><b>Integrity; add checksums to the data</b>: integrity is unaffected by using accurate data for a new purpose.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-080","domain":2,"obj":"2A7","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor reviews data governance and finds the same customer master data is duplicated across systems with conflicting values and no authoritative source. Which improvement should the auditor MOST recommend?","options":["Encrypt each copy of the data separately","Increase backup frequency for all systems","Restrict all users to read-only access","Establish a master data management approach with a system of record"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Establish a master data management approach with a system of record</strong> — designating an authoritative system of record and applying master data management resolves conflicting duplicates and ensures a single trusted version of the data.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Encrypt each copy of the data separately</b>: encryption protects confidentiality but does nothing to reconcile conflicting values.</span><span class='qd'><b>Increase backup frequency for all systems</b>: more backups preserve inconsistent data, not fix it.</span><span class='qd'><b>Restrict all users to read-only access</b>: read-only access does not create an authoritative source or resolve conflicts.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-081","domain":2,"obj":"2B1","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor reviews IT investment governance and finds business cases are prepared but benefits are never measured after projects close. What is the MOST significant weakness?","options":["Business cases are unnecessary if benefits are tracked","Projects will automatically fail without post-implementation reviews","The absence of benefits realization tracking means value delivery is unverified","IT investment cannot be budgeted without benefits tracking"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>The absence of benefits realization tracking means value delivery is unverified</strong> — without measuring realized benefits against the business case, the organization cannot confirm investments delivered the promised value, undermining investment governance.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Business cases are unnecessary if benefits are tracked</b>: business cases remain essential to justify investment; the gap is post-project measurement.</span><span class='qd'><b>Projects will automatically fail without post-implementation reviews</b>: lack of reviews hides outcomes but does not guarantee failure.</span><span class='qd'><b>IT investment cannot be budgeted without benefits tracking</b>: budgeting can occur; the weakness is unverified value, not inability to budget.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-082","domain":2,"obj":"2B2","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing supply-chain risk. A vendor stores the organization's data in a country with weak data-protection law and uses undisclosed subcontractors. Which combination of controls is MOST appropriate?","options":["Contractual data-location and subcontractor-approval clauses plus a right to audit","Only an NDA with the vendor","A verbal assurance from the vendor's sales team","Relying on the vendor's website privacy statement"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Contractual data-location and subcontractor-approval clauses plus a right to audit</strong> — binding clauses controlling where data resides and requiring approval of subcontractors, combined with audit rights, provide enforceable oversight of supply-chain and fourth-party risk.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Only an NDA with the vendor</b>: an NDA protects confidentiality but does not control data location or subcontractors.</span><span class='qd'><b>A verbal assurance from the vendor's sales team</b>: verbal assurances are unenforceable and unverifiable.</span><span class='qd'><b>Relying on the vendor's website privacy statement</b>: a public statement is not an enforceable contractual control.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-083","domain":2,"obj":"2B3","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor evaluates IT performance reporting and finds metrics are gathered but never compared to targets, trends, or peers, and no action results. What conclusion is MOST appropriate?","options":["The metrics are technically inaccurate","Reporting frequency is too low","The organization has too many KPIs","The measurement process is not driving performance improvement"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>The measurement process is not driving performance improvement</strong> — metrics deliver value only when analyzed against targets and trends and used to drive action; data collected without such use does not improve performance.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The metrics are technically inaccurate</b>: the scenario indicates unused metrics, not inaccurate ones.</span><span class='qd'><b>Reporting frequency is too low</b>: frequency is not the described issue; use of the data is.</span><span class='qd'><b>The organization has too many KPIs</b>: quantity is not stated to be the problem; lack of action is.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-084","domain":2,"obj":"2B4","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor reviews a quality program and finds inspections catch defects late, causing costly rework, while root causes are never addressed. Which improvement aligns BEST with mature quality management?","options":["Increase the number of final inspections only","Shift toward defect prevention and root-cause elimination in the process","Reduce testing to save time","Outsource all quality control externally"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Shift toward defect prevention and root-cause elimination in the process</strong> — mature quality management emphasizes preventing defects and removing their root causes, which reduces costly late rework more effectively than added inspection.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Increase the number of final inspections only</b>: more late inspection still detects defects late without preventing them.</span><span class='qd'><b>Reduce testing to save time</b>: cutting testing would let more defects escape, worsening quality.</span><span class='qd'><b>Outsource all quality control externally</b>: outsourcing inspection does not address prevention or root causes.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-085","domain":2,"obj":"2A1","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is assessing PCI DSS scope. Management asserts that tokenizing card numbers removes systems from scope. What should the auditor verify to accept this assertion?","options":["That the tokens are printed on receipts","That tokenization is implemented so systems no longer store, process, or transmit cardholder data","That the vendor holds ISO 9001 certification","That the marketing team approved the tokens"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>That tokenization is implemented so systems no longer store, process, or transmit cardholder data</strong> — scope reduction is valid only if the tokenized environment genuinely no longer handles cardholder data; the auditor must verify this technically before accepting reduced scope.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>That the tokens are printed on receipts</b>: printing tokens does not establish scope reduction and may itself create exposure.</span><span class='qd'><b>That the vendor holds ISO 9001 certification</b>: ISO 9001 is about quality management, irrelevant to PCI scope.</span><span class='qd'><b>That the marketing team approved the tokens</b>: marketing approval has no bearing on PCI scoping.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-086","domain":2,"obj":"2A2","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor is asked to evaluate the effectiveness of IT governance. Which approach provides the MOST reliable basis for that evaluation?","options":["Interview the CIO and accept the responses as fact","Count the number of IT policies that exist","Confirm the data center is physically secure","Assess governance structures, processes, and outcomes against a recognized framework such as COBIT"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Assess governance structures, processes, and outcomes against a recognized framework such as COBIT</strong> — benchmarking governance against an established framework provides objective, comprehensive criteria to evaluate effectiveness rather than relying on unverified assertions.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Interview the CIO and accept the responses as fact</b>: unverified interview responses lack corroboration and independence.</span><span class='qd'><b>Count the number of IT policies that exist</b>: policy count says nothing about whether governance is effective.</span><span class='qd'><b>Confirm the data center is physically secure</b>: physical security is one control, not a measure of overall governance.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-087","domain":2,"obj":"2A5","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor reviews how management set the acceptable threshold for a specific operational risk metric. The threshold was chosen with no link to the board's stated risk appetite. What is the auditor's PRIMARY concern?","options":["Risk tolerances are not derived from and aligned with risk appetite","The metric should not have a threshold at all","Operational risk cannot be quantified","The board should set every individual threshold personally"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Risk tolerances are not derived from and aligned with risk appetite</strong> — operational tolerances should cascade from the board's risk appetite; a threshold set without that linkage may permit exposures the board never accepted.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The metric should not have a threshold at all</b>: thresholds are appropriate; the issue is their basis, not their existence.</span><span class='qd'><b>Operational risk cannot be quantified</b>: operational risk can be measured and given thresholds.</span><span class='qd'><b>The board should set every individual threshold personally</b>: the board sets appetite; management derives specific tolerances, so personal board setting of each is impractical and unnecessary.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-088","domain":2,"obj":"2A6","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor reviews a breach-response process and finds the organization has no defined timeline for notifying regulators of a personal-data breach. Under many privacy laws, what is the MOST likely compliance gap?","options":["Failure to encrypt backups","Failure to run vulnerability scans","Failure to meet mandatory breach-notification deadlines to authorities","Failure to maintain an asset inventory"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Failure to meet mandatory breach-notification deadlines to authorities</strong> — many privacy laws impose strict notification deadlines (for example, without undue delay and within a set number of hours); lacking a defined timeline risks missing these mandatory obligations.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Failure to encrypt backups</b>: while a security concern, it is not the notification-timeline gap described.</span><span class='qd'><b>Failure to run vulnerability scans</b>: scanning is a security practice, not the breach-notification obligation at issue.</span><span class='qd'><b>Failure to maintain an asset inventory</b>: inventory is useful but unrelated to breach-notification deadlines.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-089","domain":2,"obj":"2A7","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor evaluates a data-retention practice. The organization keeps all personal data indefinitely 'in case it is useful.' Which principle does this MOST violate, and what is the appropriate remedy?","options":["Least privilege; tighten access controls","Availability; add more storage capacity","Non-repudiation; log all access","Storage limitation; define and enforce retention and disposal schedules"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Storage limitation; define and enforce retention and disposal schedules</strong> — keeping personal data longer than necessary breaches storage limitation; the remedy is retention schedules with secure disposal when data is no longer needed.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Least privilege; tighten access controls</b>: access control does not address holding data beyond its necessary period.</span><span class='qd'><b>Availability; add more storage capacity</b>: adding storage encourages over-retention rather than remedying it.</span><span class='qd'><b>Non-repudiation; log all access</b>: logging does not reduce excessive retention of personal data.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-090","domain":2,"obj":"2B1","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor reviews capacity management and finds provisioning is reactive, occurring only after users report slow performance. What is the auditor's MOST appropriate recommendation?","options":["Disable performance monitoring to reduce noise","Implement proactive, forecast-driven capacity planning tied to business demand","Add capacity only during the annual budget cycle","Wait for outages before purchasing resources"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Implement proactive, forecast-driven capacity planning tied to business demand</strong> — capacity should be planned ahead using demand forecasts and monitoring trends so resources are ready before shortfalls degrade service.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Disable performance monitoring to reduce noise</b>: removing monitoring eliminates the very data needed to plan capacity.</span><span class='qd'><b>Add capacity only during the annual budget cycle</b>: a rigid annual cycle cannot respond to changing demand throughout the year.</span><span class='qd'><b>Wait for outages before purchasing resources</b>: reacting to outages is exactly the failure mode the recommendation must fix.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-091","domain":2,"obj":"2B2","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor reviews vendor performance governance. SLAs exist but no one reviews the vendor's reported metrics or validates them independently. What is the PRIMARY risk?","options":["The vendor cannot invoice the organization","The contract automatically renews","Undetected SLA breaches because performance is unverified","The RFP process was skipped"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Undetected SLA breaches because performance is unverified</strong> — SLAs deliver value only if performance is monitored and independently validated; unreviewed vendor self-reporting can conceal breaches and prevent enforcement of remedies.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The vendor cannot invoice the organization</b>: invoicing is unaffected by whether SLA metrics are reviewed.</span><span class='qd'><b>The contract automatically renews</b>: renewal terms are separate from performance monitoring.</span><span class='qd'><b>The RFP process was skipped</b>: the RFP occurs before contracting and is unrelated to ongoing SLA review.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-092","domain":2,"obj":"2B3","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor is assessing whether the IT balanced scorecard is well designed. Which weakness would MOST reduce its usefulness for governance?","options":["It reports only lagging financial measures and omits customer, process, and learning perspectives","It includes measures across all four perspectives","It links measures to strategic objectives","It is reviewed regularly by management"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>It reports only lagging financial measures and omits customer, process, and learning perspectives</strong> — the balanced scorecard's strength is balancing multiple perspectives; reducing it to lagging financials alone defeats its purpose and gives a one-dimensional view.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It includes measures across all four perspectives</b>: this is exactly the intended, balanced design.</span><span class='qd'><b>It links measures to strategic objectives</b>: strategic linkage is a strength, not a weakness.</span><span class='qd'><b>It is reviewed regularly by management</b>: regular review supports its usefulness.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-093","domain":2,"obj":"2B4","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor reviews the use of CMMI in the development organization. Management claims Level 5 maturity, but processes are not measured or statistically controlled. Which conclusion is MOST supportable?","options":["The claimed maturity level is not evidenced by quantitative process management","Level 5 requires no measurement of processes","The organization has exceeded Level 5","Maturity levels are irrelevant to quality"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>The claimed maturity level is not evidenced by quantitative process management</strong> — higher CMMI levels require quantitatively managed and continuously optimized processes; absent measurement and statistical control, a Level 5 claim is unsupported.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Level 5 requires no measurement of processes</b>: the opposite is true; measurement and optimization are central to the top levels.</span><span class='qd'><b>The organization has exceeded Level 5</b>: Level 5 is the highest defined level, so exceeding it is not meaningful.</span><span class='qd'><b>Maturity levels are irrelevant to quality</b>: maturity levels are directly tied to process quality and predictability.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-094","domain":2,"obj":"2A3","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor finds employees are unaware of key security policies despite the policies being formally approved. Which control weakness does this MOST indicate?","options":["Policies that are too short","An excessive number of standards","Inadequate policy communication and awareness training","A missing enterprise architecture"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Inadequate policy communication and awareness training</strong> — approved policies achieve their purpose only if communicated and reinforced through awareness training; lack of employee awareness points to a communication and training gap.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Policies that are too short</b>: length is not indicated as the cause of unawareness.</span><span class='qd'><b>An excessive number of standards</b>: the issue is awareness of policies, not the quantity of standards.</span><span class='qd'><b>A missing enterprise architecture</b>: architecture is unrelated to whether staff know the policies.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-095","domain":2,"obj":"2A4","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor reviews a target-state architecture that assumes a technology the organization has no skills or budget to adopt within the planning horizon. What is the auditor's MOST relevant observation?","options":["Target states never consider skills or budget","The target state is not realistic or achievable given constraints","The current-state architecture is therefore invalid","Enterprise architecture should ignore feasibility"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>The target state is not realistic or achievable given constraints</strong> — a useful target architecture must be attainable within the organization's resource, skill, and time constraints; ignoring feasibility yields an aspirational document that cannot guide investment.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Target states never consider skills or budget</b>: feasibility, including skills and budget, is a core input to target-state planning.</span><span class='qd'><b>The current-state architecture is therefore invalid</b>: an unrealistic target does not invalidate the documented current state.</span><span class='qd'><b>Enterprise architecture should ignore feasibility</b>: feasibility is essential to sound architecture, not something to ignore.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-096","domain":2,"obj":"2A1","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor is evaluating the organization's response to a new regulation. Management adopted the control framework but never mapped the specific regulatory requirements to its controls. What is the PRIMARY risk?","options":["The framework is automatically non-compliant","The regulation does not apply to frameworks","Controls cannot exist without a framework","Requirements may be unaddressed because coverage was never verified against the regulation"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Requirements may be unaddressed because coverage was never verified against the regulation</strong> — adopting a framework does not guarantee every specific regulatory requirement is met; without mapping requirements to controls, gaps can go undetected.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The framework is automatically non-compliant</b>: a framework is not inherently non-compliant; the risk is unverified coverage.</span><span class='qd'><b>The regulation does not apply to frameworks</b>: regulations apply to the organization regardless of the framework used.</span><span class='qd'><b>Controls cannot exist without a framework</b>: controls can exist independently; the issue is mapping to requirements.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-097","domain":2,"obj":"2A5","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor reviews management's decision to accept a risk that exceeds the documented risk appetite. The acceptance was signed by a mid-level manager. What is the auditor's PRIMARY concern?","options":["Risk should never be accepted under any circumstances","Mid-level managers cannot assess any risk","Acceptance of risk beyond appetite requires authorization at the appropriate senior level","Risk acceptance does not need documentation"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Acceptance of risk beyond appetite requires authorization at the appropriate senior level</strong> — accepting risk that exceeds the board-defined appetite must be escalated and approved by an authority with the mandate to accept it, not delegated to a mid-level manager.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Risk should never be accepted under any circumstances</b>: acceptance is a legitimate treatment when properly authorized.</span><span class='qd'><b>Mid-level managers cannot assess any risk</b>: they can assess risk; the concern is authority to accept beyond appetite.</span><span class='qd'><b>Risk acceptance does not need documentation</b>: acceptance should always be documented; the issue is the authorization level.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-098","domain":2,"obj":"2B1","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor reviews IT resource governance and finds two strategic projects competed for the same scarce specialist staff, causing both to slip. Which governance mechanism was MOST likely missing?","options":["Portfolio-level resource prioritization and allocation","A daily stand-up meeting","A firewall change window","A software escrow arrangement"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Portfolio-level resource prioritization and allocation</strong> — governing scarce resources across competing initiatives requires portfolio-level prioritization to allocate people to the highest-value work and avoid contention.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A daily stand-up meeting</b>: a team ceremony does not resolve cross-project resource contention at the portfolio level.</span><span class='qd'><b>A firewall change window</b>: a change window is a technical scheduling control, unrelated to staffing conflicts.</span><span class='qd'><b>A software escrow arrangement</b>: escrow protects code access, not resource allocation.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-099","domain":2,"obj":"2B2","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor is assessing concentration risk in vendor management. The organization relies on a single provider for a critical service with no alternative. Which risk-treatment approach BEST addresses this exposure?","options":["Sign a longer contract with the same provider","Reduce the number of SLA metrics tracked","Waive the right-to-audit clause","Develop a contingency and alternative-sourcing strategy to reduce dependency"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Develop a contingency and alternative-sourcing strategy to reduce dependency</strong> — single-source concentration risk is best mitigated by contingency plans and identifying alternative providers so a failure does not leave the organization without the critical service.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Sign a longer contract with the same provider</b>: a longer term deepens dependency rather than reducing concentration risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>Reduce the number of SLA metrics tracked</b>: fewer metrics weaken oversight and do nothing for concentration risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>Waive the right-to-audit clause</b>: waiving audit rights reduces assurance and worsens the exposure.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-100","domain":2,"obj":"2A2","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor is asked by the audit committee to give an overall opinion on IT governance. Which of the following would the auditor MOST appropriately conclude governance is effective when observed?","options":["The IT budget is the largest line item in the organization","IT is aligned with strategy, risks are managed within appetite, resources are optimized, and value is measured","All IT decisions are made solely by the CIO","There have been no help desk tickets this quarter"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>IT is aligned with strategy, risks are managed within appetite, resources are optimized, and value is measured</strong> — effective IT governance is demonstrated by strategic alignment, risk management within appetite, resource optimization, and measured value delivery, which together reflect the governance objectives.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The IT budget is the largest line item in the organization</b>: spending size is not a measure of governance effectiveness.</span><span class='qd'><b>All IT decisions are made solely by the CIO</b>: concentrating all decisions in one role signals weak governance, not strong.</span><span class='qd'><b>There have been no help desk tickets this quarter</b>: absence of tickets is implausible and unrelated to governance quality.</span>"}
]);
